3.    `getEvents<T>(from?: Date, to?: Date): T[];`

title: [node] Correct constants module for node v6
body:
# Environment

Nodejs 6.5.0
# Description

Based on interest. I tried to trace #11022. I get amazing discovery as following:

In fact, there are **136** exported properties of  constants in **Nodejs**.
But there are **271** exported properties of  constants in **node.d.ts**.
The quantity is not consistency.

Sample code:

```
const c = constants;
Object.keys(constants).length
// 136
```

134 in 136 properties have been defined in **node.d.ts**. The 2 missing properties are **['ENGINE_METHOD_RSA', 'ALPN_ENABLED']**, so I had added in definition.

137 in 271 exported properties of  constants in **node.d.ts** are unknown properties. To avoid causing unknown issues, it keeps in place, it's in order to discuss on next issue or PR, so it decided to not be deleted. Therefore, I used comments `/// The following needs to be reviewed` to split them.
# Actions

In **node.d.ts**:
- Add missing stuff: **'ENGINE_METHOD_RSA', 'ALPN_ENABLED'**
- Use comments to split into real and unknown properties

In **node-tests.ts**:
- Add tests for **constants**

title: [types-2.0] d3-array (Test Adjustment)
body:
Change to existing definitions test for **d3-array**. This is related to the issue flagged by @aleung in PR #11184 .

@RyanCavanaugh 

**This is considered a temporary fix so that the DT/types-2.0 branch stays intact for other merges.**

However, the reason for the error flagged in the latest DefinitelyTyped Test Runner may be due to a regression in TypeScript@next (2.1.0-dev.20160912 or 2.1.0-dev.20160913).

The definition for the `extent(...)` function includes the following overload:

```
/**
 * Return the min and max simultaneously.
 */
export function extent<T extends Numeric>(array: Array<T | Primitive>): [T | Primitive, T | Primitive] | [undefined, undefined];
```

The now failing test seems due to the fact that `T` is no longer inferred as `NumCoercible`, but only as `Numeric`.

_Applied temporary fix:_
- Add explicit typing to an `extent` test with mixed array including NumCoercible.

# Action
- Add

- Delete

    - An interface doesn't need to extends  `EventEmitter`-like twice, otherwise it will show `someoneType simultaneously extend types EventEmitter and anotherType`.
    - Refer [export interface Server extends events.EventEmitter, net.Server](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/11217/commits/4d6e4d7853b2a13bf31f0f2cd985aaab4afd1387#diff-bf89eb87012559957ad998badfd53de5L591). The `net.Server` has included `EventEmitter`. It doesn't need to extend `events.EventEmitter` again.
    - [ServerResponse](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/11217/commits/4d6e4d7853b2a13bf31f0f2cd985aaab4afd1387#diff-bf89eb87012559957ad998badfd53de5L602),[ClientRequest](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/11217/commits/4d6e4d7853b2a13bf31f0f2cd985aaab4afd1387#diff-bf89eb87012559957ad998badfd53de5L602), [IncomingMessage](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/11217/commits/4d6e4d7853b2a13bf31f0f2cd985aaab4afd1387#diff-bf89eb87012559957ad998badfd53de5L632) are same reason.
- Modify

title: [node] connection are socket are same in IncomingMessage
body:
# Improvement to existing type definition.

It doesn't be mentioned in the document. It needs to refer to source code.

When initializing a `IncomingMessage` instance, it will set `socket` to [this.socket](https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/357f904169c39bbc9c2d8558bbffce2337c83c1b/lib/_http_incoming.js#L30) and [this.connection](https://github.com/nodejs/node/blob/357f904169c39bbc9c2d8558bbffce2337c83c1b/lib/_http_incoming.js#L31).

The `this.socket` is [message.socket](https://nodejs.org/dist/latest-v6.x/docs/api/http.html#http_message_socket) on document and It's a [net.Socket](https://nodejs.org/dist/latest-v6.x/docs/api/net.html#net_class_net_socket) object.

 Therefore, `this.socket` and `this.connection` get same object and the object is `net.Socket`.

title: AmCharts definitions generated from scraped HTML documenation (#11090)
body:
As discussed in #11090 I have re-created the full definitions file based on an automatic scraping process which takes the HTML documentation at https://docs.amcharts.com/3/ and applies some magic (text parsing, hardcoded snippets based on property and type names mentioned in the HTML docs).

Upon requect I can make this tool available, source is .NET but the generation code is completely in XSLT.

Notes/Caveats:
- The "Class Reference" documentation seems to be incomplete. For instance, `isReady`and its cousin `ready()` are both not in the docs, as well as some types auch as `AmExport`. I have added whatever I stumbled across but I have not manually diffed everything to the original AmCharts.d.ts file, so using my definitions _may_ break code.
- There are three "families" of charts offered by AmCharts: the normal JavaScript charts, the extended stock charts, and the map charts. The latter two each include some or all of the JavaScript charts, but their documentation quality is worse, even for classes which are found in both families. Therefore the tool processes all standard chart documentation URLs, then all the ones from the stock charts which have not yet been done as part of the standard charts. I had to omit the maps because the documentation is unfortunately too poor for being handled by a tool. I've added details about this to issue #10671
